01:09:45,957 --> 01:09:47,293
Yes, Sister.

791
01:09:48,794 --> 01:09:51,255
What can I do?

792
01:09:51,297 --> 01:09:54,133
He is the man
that God has given me, and...

793
01:09:55,592 --> 01:09:58,262
why would he do that
if there wasn't a reason for it?

794
01:09:59,805 --> 01:10:04,601
God will not lead you
to the desert and abandon you.

795
01:10:05,686 --> 01:10:10,482
The dutiful wife who prays
for husband and family

796
01:10:10,524 --> 01:10:12,984
will be heard first.

797
01:10:13,026 --> 01:10:15,821
Continue to pray.

798
01:10:15,862 --> 01:10:18,574
Increase your offering.

799
01:10:18,615 --> 01:10:20,451
You cannot give up.

800
01:10:20,492 --> 01:10:24,621
Now, bow your head.
Let's pray together.

801
01:10:24,663 --> 01:10:30,001
Heavenly Father, we come
before you with Sister Esther.

802
01:10:30,043 --> 01:10:34,506
Lord, we ask you to give her peace...

803
01:11:02,576 --> 01:11:04,453
Mae?

804
01:11:45,035 --> 01:11:46,203
You're not going to continue

805
01:11:46,245 --> 01:11:49,080
with the stage lights
and promotion?

806
01:11:49,122 --> 01:11:51,458
Not unless you become
a famous dancer, Miss Sylvia.

807
01:11:55,546 --> 01:11:58,048
Sylvia.

808
01:11:58,089 --> 01:11:59,675
She's a teenager.

809
01:11:59,716 --> 01:12:01,302
It's her job to annoy us.

810
01:12:01,343 --> 01:12:04,721
- Mm.- She'll just calm down.

811
01:12:04,763 --> 01:12:06,557
Let's just take a moment.

812
01:12:06,598 --> 01:12:08,684
Let's... let's go out to dinner
so we can talk.

813
01:12:08,725 --> 01:12:10,894
I don't think you understand,
Walter.

814
01:12:10,936 --> 01:12:13,814
This is not a time
for going out to dinner.

815
01:12:13,855 --> 01:12:15,899
Clearly, we need to be at home
watching our daughter.

816
01:12:22,864 --> 01:12:25,492
- Who?
- Esther.

817
01:12:25,534 --> 01:12:26,868
Who?

818
01:12:26,910 --> 01:12:28,662
Esther!

819
01:12:28,704 --> 01:12:31,081
Walter's wife.

820
01:12:33,584 --> 01:12:35,711
Hey, queen. How are you?

821
01:12:35,752 --> 01:12:38,046
Oh, fine, thank you.

822
01:12:38,088 --> 01:12:40,966
I, um... I wanted to ask you
a favor, please, my sister.

823
01:12:41,007 --> 01:12:42,217
Mm-hm?

824
01:12:42,259 --> 01:12:44,219
I'm going to dinner
with Walter tonight,

825
01:12:44,261 --> 01:12:46,305
and I... I need to borrow

826
01:12:46,347 --> 01:12:48,432
just a purse
to go with this outfit.

827
01:12:50,476 --> 01:12:53,479
Mm-mm. Mm-mm.

828
01:12:53,520 --> 01:12:56,690
Girl, you're... you're gonna need
way more than just a purse.

829
01:12:56,732 --> 01:12:59,067
Mm-mm. Come on.

830
01:13:00,944 --> 01:13:02,279
Come on.

831
01:13:04,865 --> 01:13:08,702
So, where are you
going for dinner?

832
01:13:08,744 --> 01:13:11,413
Well, I'm not sure.
He didn't tell me.

833
01:13:11,455 --> 01:13:14,333
Oh, so, it's a surprise.

834
01:13:14,375 --> 01:13:16,585
All right. That's nice of him!

835
01:13:16,627 --> 01:13:20,714
Well, actually, we have been
talking about this for a while,

836
01:13:20,756 --> 01:13:24,092
but... today's not really
a good day for it.

837
01:13:24,134 --> 01:13:25,677
That's nonsense.

838
01:13:25,719 --> 01:13:28,555
Life is short.
You can't put this on hold.

839
01:13:31,224 --> 01:13:32,559
Okay.

840
01:13:32,601 --> 01:13:35,270
I agree. You are right.

841
01:13:35,312 --> 01:13:38,399
Good. So...

842
01:13:38,440 --> 01:13:42,944
we need you looking royal.

843
01:13:42,986 --> 01:13:45,071
Mm-hm.

844
01:13:45,113 --> 01:13:47,658
Well, actually,
I am a Christian,

845
01:13:47,699 --> 01:13:50,911
so, nothing too...

846
01:13:50,952 --> 01:13:54,373
Mm. Honey,

847
01:13:54,415 --> 01:13:56,708
you're out here worried
about another woman's mail

848
01:13:56,750 --> 01:13:59,169
when you're hiding the essence
of your womanhood

849
01:13:59,210 --> 01:14:00,504
from your own husband.

850
01:14:00,546 --> 01:14:03,214
Is that really what
white Jesus wants?

851
01:14:09,179 --> 01:14:12,974
Sometimes a king needs his queen

852
01:14:13,016 --> 01:14:16,520
to remind him who she is.

853
01:14:16,562 --> 01:14:18,063
Now, come on.

854
01:14:27,948 --> 01:14:29,950
You look...

855
01:14:31,034 --> 01:14:33,412
very beautiful.

856
01:14:33,454 --> 01:14:35,414
I'm glad you like it.

857
01:14:35,456 --> 01:14:36,790
Can I get you anything else?

858
01:14:36,832 --> 01:14:38,792
Oh, coffee, please.

859
01:14:38,834 --> 01:14:40,919
- Ma'am?
- Oh, no. Thank you.

860
01:14:43,422 --> 01:14:44,798
Thank you for bringing me here.

861
01:14:44,840 --> 01:14:46,717
It's... it's very nice.

862
01:14:59,480 --> 01:15:03,484
Remember when life was simple?

863
01:15:05,402 --> 01:15:09,656
When a fancy night
was sitting on the beach,

864
01:15:09,698 --> 01:15:11,933
grilling fish over a fire...

865
01:15:13,326 --> 01:15:14,953
with cheap wine?

866
01:15:17,372 --> 01:15:20,959
Red snapper with jindungo,
of course.

867
01:15:21,001 --> 01:15:23,629
And plantains.

868
01:15:23,670 --> 01:15:26,423
From Dona Magalie's place
on the corner.

869
01:15:26,465 --> 01:15:29,009
Did she survive?

870
01:15:32,262 --> 01:15:35,557
I'm... not even sure.

871
01:15:35,599 --> 01:15:38,268
After we left for Tanzania,

872
01:15:38,309 --> 01:15:40,979
I lost touch
with so many people.

873
01:16:02,668 --> 01:16:03,710
Let's dance.

874
01:16:05,629 --> 01:16:08,507
- Where?
- Here, on the side.

875
01:16:08,549 --> 01:16:11,176
- We can't do that.
- Why not?

876
01:16:11,217 --> 01:16:12,302
The band's warming up.

877
01:16:12,343 --> 01:16:14,888
Shouldn't we wait for them
to start the party properly?

878
01:16:16,723 --> 01:16:20,060
I'm not stopping. Come.

879
01:16:20,101 --> 01:16:21,562
Join me.

880
01:16:21,603 --> 01:16:24,773
You are embarrassing yourself.

881
01:16:24,815 --> 01:16:26,525
Then come rescue me, huh?

882
01:16:26,567 --> 01:16:29,653
We'll be embarrassed together.

883
01:16:46,169 --> 01:16:48,129
See?

884
01:16:49,427 --> 01:16:50,465
It's working!

885
01:16:50,490 --> 01:16:52,676
It's been so long.
I don't even remember how.

886
01:17:03,770 --> 01:17:05,772
You're always the most beautiful...

887
01:17:07,941 --> 01:17:10,276
when you dance.

888
01:18:19,971 --> 01:18:22,891
From the donation box.

889
01:18:30,982 --> 01:18:32,943
Wait, wait, don't do that.

890
01:18:32,984 --> 01:18:34,945
- I'll get rid of them!
- Esther, no.

891
01:18:34,986 --> 01:18:38,198
I've heard you, Walter,
loud and clear.

892
01:18:38,239 --> 01:18:41,201
You don't want me.

893
01:18:41,242 --> 01:18:43,662
You want something else.

894
01:18:46,456 --> 01:18:48,083
This...

895
01:18:48,124 --> 01:18:51,712
This was too big for us
to not lose ourselves.

896
01:18:55,548 --> 01:18:58,844
I... I want to go back home.

897
01:19:16,527 --> 01:19:19,698
Everybody thinks
her father abandoned us,

898
01:19:19,740 --> 01:19:21,700
that she was born from disgrace,

899
01:19:21,742 --> 01:19:23,534
and that's why
you never came back.

900
01:19:23,576 --> 01:19:25,286
She wasn't born from disgrace!

901
01:19:25,328 --> 01:19:27,622
After you left,
my parents disowned me

902
01:19:27,664 --> 01:19:29,833
and took their curses
to their graves!

903
01:20:07,620 --> 01:20:11,082
I need to know who she is.

904
01:20:17,130 --> 01:20:19,132
You ready to kill it
at the cypher tonight?

905
01:20:19,174 --> 01:20:22,427
Yeah. Neema made me
a special dance mix.

906
01:20:38,944 --> 01:20:40,570
Write your stage name on here.

907
01:21:07,555 --> 01:21:11,351
When you get out there,
you forget about your parents.

908
01:21:11,392 --> 01:21:14,062
Forget about everything.
You're gonna kill it.

909
01:21:15,939 --> 01:21:17,440
Thanks, DJ.

910
01:21:17,482 --> 01:21:19,025
For what?

911
01:21:19,067 --> 01:21:20,318
For believing.

912
01:21:20,360 --> 01:21:21,945
You know I got you.

913
01:21:21,987 --> 01:21:23,780
It ain't really nothing.

914
01:21:36,251 --> 01:21:38,336
All, right, well, let's...
Let's get going.

915
01:21:53,101 --> 01:21:55,645
I'm looking for my daughter.

916
01:21:55,686 --> 01:21:57,188
She's a dancer.

917
01:22:06,197 --> 01:22:08,574
Next.

918
01:22:17,792 --> 01:22:19,210
That's Wreckka.

919
01:22:19,252 --> 01:22:21,296
Watch her closely.
She's the one to beat.

920
01:22:33,975 --> 01:22:36,686
All right, all right, all right.
Repping Philly,

921
01:22:36,727 --> 01:22:40,899
we have... Dirty Dozen!

922
01:22:44,986 --> 01:22:49,115
Repping New York,
our reigning champion, Wreckka!

923
01:22:51,534 --> 01:22:52,911
We have a winner.

924
01:22:55,872 --> 01:22:58,249
All right, guys,
let's take a five-minute break

925
01:22:58,291 --> 01:22:59,792
before we get to this next round.

926
01:23:04,755 --> 01:23:05,995
Just stay focused.

927
01:23:07,550 --> 01:23:11,596
I think you got this
competition wrapped up.

928
01:23:13,556 --> 01:23:17,310
The audience is live.
The judges are gonna love it.

929
01:23:17,352 --> 01:23:20,105
You're amazing.
Just focus in and loosen up.

930
01:23:20,146 --> 01:23:22,523
Focus and...

931
01:23:23,461 --> 01:23:24,461
Yes.

932
01:23:25,693 --> 01:23:27,528
Hey, where you going?

933
01:23:27,570 --> 01:23:29,530
- I have to go.
- Wait, what...

934
01:23:29,572 --> 01:23:31,657
- I made a mistake, all right?
- What do you mean?

935
01:23:31,699 --> 01:23:33,243
I have to go.

936
01:23:33,284 --> 01:23:35,245
Sylvia! Hold on.

937
01:23:44,545 --> 01:23:46,756
I have to go find her.

938
01:23:52,262 --> 01:23:53,972
She's all I have.

939
01:23:54,014 --> 01:23:57,058
This is my responsibility, ViÃ±ha.

940
01:23:58,851 --> 01:23:59,851
Go.

941
01:24:01,021 --> 01:24:03,439
Fight for your dance, huh?

942
01:24:05,066 --> 01:24:07,068
I'll find her.

943
01:24:53,781 --> 01:24:55,575
Up next, ladies and gentlemen,

944
01:24:55,616 --> 01:24:57,452
our defending champion, Wreckka,

945
01:24:57,493 --> 01:24:58,995
has agreed to a battle
with the new kid on the block,

946
01:24:59,037 --> 01:25:01,664
Young Afrikka!

947
01:25:39,077 --> 01:25:40,911
No.

948
01:25:43,289 --> 01:25:44,332
No.

949
01:28:24,242 --> 01:28:26,327
I've been lost too.

950
01:28:31,291 --> 01:28:34,126
And Linda found you.

951
01:28:36,128 --> 01:28:38,673
She gave me hope, Esther.

952
01:28:38,714 --> 01:28:41,467
She insisted I don't give up,

953
01:28:41,509 --> 01:28:46,222
that I keep petitioning immigration
for us to be together.

954
01:29:01,321 --> 01:29:04,907
- You think it was easy for me?
- Of course not.

955
01:29:05,825 --> 01:29:08,536
We lost so many years.

956
01:29:11,121 --> 01:29:12,873
Look, I'm sorry.

957
01:29:18,045 --> 01:29:22,174
We don't even
know each other anymore,

958
01:29:22,216 --> 01:29:24,302
or ourselves.

959
01:29:27,972 --> 01:29:30,057
When we met...

960
01:29:33,018 --> 01:29:36,021
we didn't know if we'd live
to see the next day.

961
01:29:37,231 --> 01:29:40,485
We didn't know
who was a comrade,

962
01:29:40,526 --> 01:29:42,570
who was an informant,

963
01:29:42,612 --> 01:29:45,155
who was there for the ride.

964
01:29:48,951 --> 01:29:50,578
Words meant nothing.

965
01:29:53,498 --> 01:29:56,376
So, we danced.

966
01:29:57,918 --> 01:30:00,212
When I moved, you followed.

967
01:30:02,382 --> 01:30:05,635
When you hesitate,
I slowed down...

968
01:30:09,138 --> 01:30:11,432
because we could feel
each other.

969
01:30:20,400 --> 01:30:22,402
So...

970
01:30:26,155 --> 01:30:28,699
what do we do now?

971
01:32:21,103 --> 01:32:22,730
Mae?

972
01:32:28,528 --> 01:32:30,613
Pai said you went dancing.

973
01:32:30,655 --> 01:32:32,490
What happened?

974
01:32:34,283 --> 01:32:37,202
The crowd...

975
01:32:37,244 --> 01:32:39,163
they really liked me, Mama.

976
01:32:44,126 --> 01:32:45,628
They saw me.

977
01:32:45,670 --> 01:32:47,922
Of course they did.

978
01:32:50,174 --> 01:32:52,927
We see you.

979
01:32:52,968 --> 01:32:54,762
We do.

980
01:33:05,648 --> 01:33:07,733
I'll make us breakfast.

981
01:34:21,431 --> 01:34:23,433
Which one?

982
01:34:23,475 --> 01:34:25,603
This one.

983
01:34:25,645 --> 01:34:28,022
Your favorite biscuits.

984
01:34:39,659 --> 01:34:42,286
I like it.

985
01:34:53,463 --> 01:34:54,882
Do you want?

986
01:34:54,924 --> 01:34:56,425
Mm-hm. Thank you.

987
01:42:16,623 --> 01:42:19,183
Hi, my name is John Akomfrah.

988
01:42:19,223 --> 01:42:22,023
I'm an artist and a film-maker

989
01:42:22,063 --> 01:42:26,783
and I'm here to talk to you today
about Farewell Amor,

990
01:42:26,823 --> 01:42:28,583
which is a film you've just seen.

991
01:42:28,623 --> 01:42:33,503
And I'm very, very lucky
to have next to me Ekwa Msangi,

992
01:42:33,543 --> 01:42:38,143
who's both a director -the director, rather - and an ally.

993
01:42:38,183 --> 01:42:41,183
Am I okay to say "director and ally"?

994
01:42:41,223 --> 01:42:44,663
Yeah, absolutely.
I should certainly hope so!

995
01:42:46,983 --> 01:42:50,543
When we met,
one of the things I was convinced about

996
01:42:50,583 --> 01:42:57,103
was that you wanted to make projects
about the African experience in New York,

997
01:42:57,143 --> 01:42:58,303
where you were at the time.

998
01:42:58,343 --> 01:43:04,143
Yeah, so Farewell Amor is a project
that's been sort of stewing in my mind

999
01:43:04,183 --> 01:43:07,343
for a long time,
because it's a family story.

1000
01:43:07,383 --> 01:43:10,983
It's inspired by an aunt and an uncle

1001
01:43:11,023 --> 01:43:13,983
who were married
in the mid '90s, in Tanzania.

1002
01:43:14,023 --> 01:43:17,383
And my uncle got a student visa
to come to the US

1003
01:43:17,423 --> 01:43:22,223
and had every intention of bringing Auntie
and cousin right behind him.

1004
01:43:22,263 --> 01:43:27,423
And, to date, they've still been stuck
in visa applications, visa rejections,

1005
01:43:27,463 --> 01:43:29,783
visa application, visa rejections
for decades.

1006
01:43:29,823 --> 01:43:34,503
Watching their struggle
for so many years,

1007
01:43:34,543 --> 01:43:36,583
I wanted to make the "what if?" story.

1008
01:43:36,623 --> 01:43:39,823
I had this image in my mind
of my uncle, you know,

1009
01:43:39,863 --> 01:43:43,503
"What if Auntie finally got her visa?
That's no longer the issue.

1010
01:43:43,543 --> 01:43:46,663
"They're coming. They're coming.
It's a done deal.

1011
01:43:46,703 --> 01:43:51,943
"You know, and so Uncle's at the airport,
at arrivals gate,

1012
01:43:51,983 --> 01:43:55,423
"and he's, like, what is he...
what is he thinking?

1013
01:43:55,463 --> 01:43:57,543
"What is he feeling?
Would he recognise them?

1014
01:43:57,583 --> 01:43:59,063
"What is the first thing to say?"

1015
01:43:59,103 --> 01:44:00,983
- Amor!
- You know, for me,

1016
01:44:01,023 --> 01:44:04,823
New York is a place
that has all sorts of people like that,

1017
01:44:04,863 --> 01:44:07,183
not just African immigrants,
you know?

1018
01:44:07,223 --> 01:44:11,103
Everybody is that, and including
a lot of the white immigrants

1019
01:44:11,143 --> 01:44:14,743
that came to New York
through Ellis Island, way back when,

1020
01:44:14,783 --> 01:44:18,383
who left behind everything
in Ireland and Scotland,

1021
01:44:18,423 --> 01:44:22,183
and wherever else they came from,
to start this new place.

1022
01:44:22,223 --> 01:44:24,023
As you may be aware,

1023
01:44:24,063 --> 01:44:28,303
I'm a child
of one of those exiles in the film.

1024
01:44:28,343 --> 01:44:29,983
Yes.

1025
01:44:30,023 --> 01:44:36,103
And it is very much in the context
of your unfolding story

1026
01:44:36,143 --> 01:44:38,863
that I arrived here, you know,

1027
01:44:38,903 --> 01:44:44,503
except that I came with one parent
and one who couldn't join,

1028
01:44:44,543 --> 01:44:47,383
because they died in a coup, basically.

1029
01:44:47,423 --> 01:44:49,543
And I was really struck

1030
01:44:49,583 --> 01:44:55,623
by how different
that story that you have here

1031
01:44:55,663 --> 01:44:59,703
is from the other New York Africa stories.

1032
01:44:59,743 --> 01:45:03,943
I mean, was that a conscious attempt
to try and avoid the other ones, or...?

1033
01:45:03,983 --> 01:45:06,663
Do you know what I mean?
There's a very...

1034
01:45:06,703 --> 01:45:09,943
There's a way in which stories
are made about Africans in New York,

1035
01:45:09,983 --> 01:45:12,143
and this doesn't feel like one of them.

1036
01:45:12,183 --> 01:45:16,983
Most of the films that at least I've seen,
or that tend to be popularised,

1037
01:45:17,023 --> 01:45:21,383
certainly funded
through a Hollywood-type system

1038
01:45:21,423 --> 01:45:25,543
tend to be about either
the most exceptional African ever,

1039
01:45:25,583 --> 01:45:31,023
or the most, sort of, destitute,
struggling African ever.

1040
01:45:31,063 --> 01:45:33,463
Yes, it's a story of immigrants,

1041
01:45:33,503 --> 01:45:35,183
but I wasn't very much interested

1042
01:45:35,223 --> 01:45:39,183
in talking about the political aspects
of their immigration,

1043
01:45:39,223 --> 01:45:41,783
which tends to be
the other type of stories,

1044
01:45:41,823 --> 01:45:45,383
sort of like the cause, the issue-driven.

1045
01:45:45,423 --> 01:45:48,903
You know, what happens
when they got to the border,

1046
01:45:48,943 --> 01:45:53,103
